"Yes, sir. They must be on their way now; we gave them time to pick up rations at the mess." At exactly 5 o'clock, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
"We're deploying towards FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the upcoming attack on Ianlos to crush the uprising. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board."
The company dispersed, each joining their respective unit, and the sergeants got them into the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, his legs hanging down, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, has Harris still got Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced towards one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his backpack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he's still got it," replied Cohren as the tank turret opened with a clatter to let through its commander.
"All the tanks were en route," declared calmly but clearly the commander through his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to move. The Kronos on which Cohren was riding jolted when its brakes were released and it moved to form up. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. Winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits, whom Cohren recalled as Orson, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, haven't you?"
"Yep, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd be done in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"To underestimate is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Damn, we should be able to see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold strong for the Federation," said Orson, a bit provocative. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that new recruits like you turn to cover as soon as they hear gunfire," declared Craith.
"I think we'll soon find out," said Cohren with a laugh. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures about 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed onto the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," replied Cohren through his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked another recruit, Natayla.
"Can't tell for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Company Exodus, do not fire unless fired upon, let's get them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, grabbed it, and then sprinted back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts," shouted Shaw into the radio, while tracer rounds from the crest were being fired. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from the vehicles to take cover behind them. A anti-tank missile whizzed by and slammed into the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew extricated themselves and dived for cover as the ammunition caught fire.
"Iron 1-2 and -25 degrees right, 275 meters. Fire," yelled the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells streaking towards the crest and exploding, throwing dirt and rocks into the air.
"Send the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the crest through binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened up and an unarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone and two Sentinels, or officially Sentinelles, darted outside. Their thin metallic limbs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were strapped to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched.
"It seems we are capturing them," stepped in Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared in a cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the crest but ceased quickly. Moments later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged in the ground. Once they were safe with the platoon, they dropped the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed in the mud and snow.
Shaw marched towards the individual, who was beginning to rise. He turned towards one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you kindly dispose of this man?"
